From:    bontchev@fbihh.informatik.uni-hamburg.de (Vesselin Bontchev)
Subject: Re: SCAN 95b doesn't find MtE in EXE files (PC)

cjkuo@ccmail.norton.com (Jimmy Kuo) writes:

> >I would like to ask all those who belong to the second school of
> >thought: Will you really want to reply for virus protection on a
> >program that misses one infected file in every N? Especially if you
> >know that there are programs that -don't- miss any files infected by
> >this virus? If yes, then for what values of N? One infection missed in
> >every 50? In every 100? In every 1,000? In every 10,000?

> Vesselin, this is obviously governed by 1) whether there's money at
> stake and 2) whether you own one of those that manages 100% detection.

OK, but you still didn't answer my question. My question was aimed
towards those who think that they can live with imperfect detection.
Note, I didn't say imperfect MtE detection - after all, the current
MtE-based viruses are not spread at all.

My question is just that: suppose you are given a scanners that misses
one infected file in every N for a particular virus. For what values
of N will be happy to live with? If there is no simple answer, i.e.,
if the answer is related with the value of the information on your PC,
with the speed increase as a function of N, with the spread of the
virus that is missed, then just give me some examples. Not only you; I
am asking this questions to all readers of Virus-L/comp.virus. Also
consider the possibility that there -are- some scanners which will
- -not- miss any infected files AND will not give any false positives.

> The idea right now regarding MtE is, because the files can't readily be
> repaired, if someone is actually hit by MtE, they WILL require help.

What do you mean by "the files can't readily be repaired"? That the
MtE-based viruses cannot be disinfected? But this is simply not true;
there are several product on the market which a doing this. Or, at
least, they are claiming to do it - I have not done detailed tests,
because (1) testing for disinfection is more difficult (all your test
set has to be rebuilt after each test) and (2) I have always claimed
that virus disinfection is a bad idea.

But, if you are interested, CPAV 1.3 does disinfect some MtE-based
viruses, AntiVir IV too... A Russian anti-virus program from Eugene
Kaspersky does it too, but I have not received a copy of it yet, so I
cannot test it. Furthermore, the generic disinfector TbClean from the
ThunderByte Anti-Virus package (version 5.01, shareware, available
from Simtel20) can be used to disinfect the MtE-based viruses too. It
works most of the time, especially with COM files (with EXE files,
some fields in the EXE header are not restored, but this is properly
explained in the documentation).

> And, as has been pointed out in a different posting, they call in the
> big guns.  And the big guns bring along different tools, presumably tools
> which will detect 100%.

If you bother to read the results of my tests carefully, you'll see
that the "big guns" (CPAV, NAV, SCAN) failed, while a small freeware
program (CatchMtE) succeeded...

> Certainly it is better to have 100% than 99% than 50%.  There is no
> debate there.  And 100% is always the goal.  But remember yet another
> comment elsewhere, all this must be weighed against the common scenario
> that an antivirus program is run most often in a virus-free environment
> and must not be intrusive.

Agreed. What the user needs is a 100% reliable detector that gives no
false positives. No disagreement here. My point was that some of the
tested scanners -did- achieve this. But NAV 2.1 beta 14 didn't.

> It is fair in an academic environment to compare the standalone MtE
> detector with the full blown anti-virus package claiming to detect MtEs.
> But it is not fair to make this comparison in a commercial environment
> without a whole bunch of factors which are not covered (speed, size, ease
> of use, ...).

What the users actually need is reliable protection. Unfortunately,
they are not competent to evaluate which anti-virus protection is
reliable - they are able to evaluate only the speed, size, easy of
use, etc. That's why I am not testing these things - they can test
them themselves. Besides, the computer magazines are full of
anti-virus reviews that test only the above qualities...

What I am testing is the actual protection that the product provides -
because I have the necessary knowledge to do it. I am publishing my
results, to share this knowledge with the users. I understand very well,
that this is not the quality that "sells" the product, so many
producers are unhappy when I demonstrate that a nice looking, easy to
use, popular product provides in reality a rather poor anti-virus
protection. But this is life and I don't intend to change my position.
If some users disagree with me, they need just to stop reading my
reviews. If some producers of anti-virus software disagree with my
position, they have two options - ignore my messages, or improve their
product. The market will show which alternative is more profitable.

Back to your initial statement, I don't believe that the detection of
MtE-based viruses is only an academical issue. This virus creation
tool is relatively widely available, so we must have also widely
available reliable detectors of the viruses generated with it. It
doesn't matter how spread the -current- MtE-based viruses are - if we
don't have reliable detectors, they (or other MtE-based viruses)
- -will- become widespread.

Furthermore, there -were- full-featured scanners that were able to
show 100% reliable MtE detection in our tests. Some of them seemed to
be even faster than NAV, but I cannot claim this for sure, because I
was not interested in this issue and didn't measure the speed exactly.
Besides, (1) it is rather difficult to measure the speed difference on
a 486, and (2) it is not fair to measure the speed in an infected
environment - because the programs are usually used in a clean
environment. But, it seemed pretty much to me that F-Prot was faster
than NAV. (I do not intend to test this further, anybody who has both
products and test it for him/herself.) Furthermore, the current
detection and disinfection rate of F-Prot is also significantly higher
than the one in NAV, so F-Prot is hardly less "full-featured" than
NAV...

Even if you compare the size, F-Prot is significantly smaller than the
NAV package. What else? OK, F-Prot does not have integrity checking
and monitoring programs, but first those programs in NAV are
relatively trivial to bypass, and second, I don't see how this affects
the MtE detection.

Regards,
Vesselin
