Hello Alfred,

KARGRA@GBA930.ZAMG.AC.AT writes:
>At first I need to tell, this NO FLAME. I'm just curios. Mr. Goretsky
                               ^^^^^^^^
That's quite alright.  I'm getting used to answering all sorts
of questions, lately. :-)

>wrote, that the number after the "V" tells how many viruses are found
>by the version.  That seems somehow strange. Do you invent a new virus

The number after the "V" _used_ to be the number of viruses detected
by VIRUSCAN (SCAN.EXE).  This is why the first release of VIRUSCAN,
which detected 19 viruses, was called Version 19 instead of Version 1.
When a new virus was discovered, a new release of SCAN was made to
detect it and the version number was incremented.  This continued on
through around the 40's, at which point viruses were coming in faster
then we could release individual versions of VIRUSCAN.  So then what
we started doing is releasing a version that would detect 3 or 5 new
viruses at a time and incrementing the version number by one.  Today,
50+ viruses can be added in a single release, and the version number
will only be incremented by one.

>in order to skip a versionnumber which was already used by a trojan?

When a Trojan horse version appears, we just skip that version number
and go to the next one.

>Currently I assume, you just wait for the next virus to appear, then
>add it to the update, and skip the trojan's number. Is this the right
>way to see things ?

Correct.

