From:    padgett@tccslr.dnet.mmc.com (A. Padgett Peterson)
Subject: Re: Scanner Wars (was MtE Wars) (PC)

>From:    bontchev@fbihh.informatik.uni-hamburg.de (Vesselin Bontchev)

>Obviously, one of your requirements is that the integrity checker must
>be resident (i.e., to be an integrity shell), otherwise you would
>probably have mentioned Untouchable... 

That is correct. IMHO there needs to be a "real-time" component that 
runs essentially unnoticably.

>but don't think that Virus Buster's integrity checker is
>secure enough...

Needs some definition here, I have never seen a system that I could not
break manually that did not encrypt the entire disk (and some that did).

The question is really "is the integrity checker secure enough that it
is easier to disconnect it than to fool it ?". Note that one of my 
requirements is for a different algorithm & seed on each machine (figure
out how to fool A & it won't work on B).

> VDS is also a robust system, but unfortunately it
>is not compatible with user-installable volumes like Stacker...

The key word is "yet". It is not difficult to be "Stacker compliant",
any DOS program can do that. The DOS bypass checkers are proof against 
most stealth and *that* is more difficult to do.

>Furthermore, when the "something detector" detects that "something has
>changed", you still need a program that tells you -what- has caused
>the changes (hey, it might format the disk after 30 seconds!). You
>also need a way to detect all infected files. Integrity checking
>helps, but it cannot always determine the source of the infection.
>And, if you cannot find it, you are running the risk to get infected
>again...

Thought I had said (possibly some time ago) that integrity of the *system*
had to be a first priority. Besides, it is simple to say "NO low level
formatting without explicit approval" (something it shouldn't be doing).

>At last, the examples used by you are not very correct. MtE and
>Commander Bomber are attacks against known-virus scanning, not against
>integrity checking.

Afraid you missed the point. I have seen an IMHO disturbing trend by
some integrity checkers to use a "turbo" mode that only validates the
first and the last bytes of a file. This is not a good thing.

>Is it surprising then that they defeat the
>scanners and not the integrity checkers? How about that: worried that
>your integrity checker cannot detect Brain, or Darth Vader, or fails
>to detect the replication of StarShip...

We have discussed this. Again it comes under the heading of "system 
integrity" & is why SafeMBR was able to detect STARSHIP before that
virus had been seen. BRAIN is just as easy to detect.

>Yes, the multi-layered approach is the best solution. But you still
>need a known-virus scanner as one of the levels. Not a very strong
>level, but a necessary one...

Agree to a certain extent - I use scanners but mainly as a labor saving
device but feel they should be confined to those who know how to use
them. Disinfectors even more so.

>> As far as hardware is concerned, selection of the boot drive (C:) is
>> sufficient. If you really want to boot from a floppy, 20 bytes in the 
>> MBR (software) will let you  hold down the Ctrl key while booting to redirec
t

>> the boot to A: instead of C:. A few more bytes and you can restore the 
>> interrupt table even if you do manage to become infected first. In a single 

>Unfortunately, it also takes about 50 bytes to locate these 20 bytes
>and to change them to "do nothing" or "shut up"... :-)

Not in a "complete" system. If I can guarentee that my code will run first
(and with boot selection I can), then that code can be "armoured" and can
be later validated. Now a virus will have to find the armouring and turn it
off before it can change the "20 bytes". Sure, you or I could still spend 
some time with DEBUG and remove it, but software is not going to have an
easy time of it, particularly if I add a few ROM loops into the intercept.

Part of the problem is that what was reasonably simple four years ago has
evolved into a very complex field. I try to keep my postings simple and
confined to a single point but this is getting more and more difficult - 
I regularly spend an hour just discussing what the TOM in an IBM-PC should
look like (e.g. what CHKDSK returns & why MEM may return a different
number).


Am starting to think a book on integrity management and the IBM-PC
architecture (NOT how to write a virus) might not be a bad idea. Now
if I just had some free time...

					Warmly,
						Padgett

